I investigated this, and it's not exactly a bug but more an issue with how Python and pybind references interact.

The main issue here is that the C++ Subobject instance that you pass in `sf_(o.s)` isn't a registered instance (that is, no Python instance currently references it).  You can see this (and sort of work around it) by adding `z = os` to your Python code immediately before the `copying2.doit(...)` call: the `subject copied` line disappears from the output.

The main reason is that Python (and thus pybind) already references an instance, which means when we try to cast the `o.s` in the `sf_(o.s)` call, we see the existing reference and create a new Python reference to the existing object.  When we *don't* have an existing reference, pybind is being asked to cast the `const Subject &` into a Python object, and takes the safe path of making a copy of it (we can't reference it because we have no idea how long the reference will remain valid).  So we create a new Python wrapper around a new `Subject` copied from the input value, and pybind manages this new copy, destroying it once it goes out of scope.

Normally, this is where `return_value_policy` comes in: you can cast things with an added `return_value_policy::reference` to tell pybind that it is, in fact, safe to store a reference to the object without making a copy (in which case, it's up to the caller to make sure the reference stays valid).  `functional.h`, however, doesn't currently expose that ability, and it's not clear to me that there is any particularly nice way to add the capability in.

One workaround is to skip `functional.h` and instead take a `py::function` argument, controlling the casting to Python (and return value policies) yourself, i.e. replacing your `doit(...)` with:

```C++
void doit(const object& o, py::function sf, py::function of) {
    std::cout << "work on object:\n";
    of(py::cast(o, py::return_value_policy::reference));
    std::cout << "done\nwork on subobject:\n";
    sf(py::cast(o.s, py::return_value_policy::reference));
    std::cout << "done\n";
}
```

The pointer workaround that you discovered is *not* a valid workaround: the reason it seems to work is that when pybind is asked to cast a pointer to a Python object, it takes ownership of the pointer (by default; though again you can change that with a return value policy), which means it destroys it when the Python object gets garbage collected.  But at that point you're in Undefined Behaviour territory: it's going to try to destruct and `delete` that pointer eventually, but you definitely don't want either of those to happen.  So basically, even with a pointer, you *still* have to use `return_value_policy::reference` so that pybind knows that it can safely reference it but shouldn't manage it.

As for why the `.def_readonly` doesn't change this, it's handled dynamically: we don't actually create a python instance for the property until you actually use it.

Instead of a static local variable, how about amending the example to:

```C++
// the capsule needs a pointer to reference; if you don't have anything better, create a simple one:
int *data = new int(123);

py::capsule cleanup(&unused, [](PyObject * capsule) {
    // do cleanup here -- this function is called with the GIL held
    int *data = PyCapsule_GetPointer(capsule, nullptr);
    delete data;
});
```

which also suggests an obvious way of how to pass data into the capsule.

