It might help to give a little background on the architecture of PyNWB objects. Every PyNWB object is an instance of an [NWBBaseType](http://pynwb.readthedocs.io/en/latest/pynwb.core.html#pynwb.core.NWBBaseType), which has the attribute `parent`. This attribute, which can only be set once i.e. you can't move around Containers, is responsible for maintaining the hierarchical relationship of NWB data. This attribute is leveraged to ensure all data dependencies are written according to the specification. So, if a container has no parent, writing will break. (If you are not having this experience, please create an issue specific to this.) 

I have gone back and forth on how strict to be when enforcing specification compliance during write, and in the end, I have decided that pynwb should allow writing invalid files. I want to avoid situations where data that takes significant resources to generate cannot be written because it doesn't meet the specification. This situation would occur as NWB becomes more than an exchange format and analysis tools are writing directly to NWB, which is part of our long-term vision.
